<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="407" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[115,1324,1172,1787]" pageId="14" pageNumber="407">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[120,371,1207,1236]" pageId="14" pageNumber="407">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 61-75-5 mm, tail 38-49 mm, ear 8 mm, hindfoot 12-15 mm; weight 6 g. The Jalisco Shrew is medium-sized. Dorsum is medium brown, and venter is grayish white. Tail is ¢.60% of head-body length and unicolored medium brown. It has five unicuspids,fifth is minute, and third is slightly smaller than fourth. Teeth are pigmented dark red, including first lower incisor, which is one section of and in a long strip on the anterio-medial edge.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="407" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="14.[115,1324,1172,1787]" pageId="14" pageNumber="407">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[120,231,1439,1472]" pageId="14" pageNumber="407">Habitat.</emphasis>
High-elevation woodlands and moist montane canyons of pine-oak, pine-oakjuniper, or firjuniper forests at elevations of 1875-3048 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
